{"id":"1005.4978","submitter":"Theodore Hill","authors":"Theodore P. Hill, Jack Miller","title":"How to Combine Independent Data Sets for the Same Quantity","comments":"20 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.3593373","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.data-an math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper describes a recent mathematical method called conflation for\nconsolidating data from independent experiments that are designed to measure\nthe same quantity, such as Planck's constant or the mass of the top quark.\nConflation is easy to calculate and visualize, and minimizes the maximum loss\nin Shannon information in consolidating several independent distributions into\na single distribution. In order to benefit the experimentalist with a much more\ntransparent presentation than the previous mathematical treatise, the main\nbasic properties of conflation are derived in the special case of normal\n(Gaussian) data. Included are examples of applications to real data from\nmeasurements of the fundamental physical constants and from measurements in\nhigh energy physics, and the conflation operation is generalized to weighted\nconflation for situations when the underlying experiments are not uniformly\nreliable.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 27 May 2010 02:10:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 18 Aug 2010 17:26:45 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 9 May 2011 16:53:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-19"}
